The paper discusses a protocol for securing networks against attacks, which is a common topic in the computer security (cs.CR) and distributed computing (cs.DC) sub-categories. The paper also addresses Sybil attacks, Byzantine consensus, and Committee election, which are topics related to distributed systems (cs.DS) and system security (cs.SY). Finally, the paper discusses the computational and bandwidth costs of the protocol, which falls under the network and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
